{"id":14881805,"mediaExerciseId":"aa342bf5-6beb-4e47-a929-eda9f05b0760","exerciseName":"8","chapterName":"22","chapterTitle":"Behavioral Finance: Implications For Financial Management","groupId":612479,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":762,"solutions":[{"id":5987282,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"The theory of **behavioral finance** can explain both the 1987 crash and the 1990 rise in the price of Internet stocks as driven by the behavior and psychology of the investors. \n\nAs we all know, behavioral finance tries to explain how even experienced traders can sometimes allow their personal biases to dominate their way of trading. So in 1987, when majority of the traders thought that the stock prices have been rising for a prolonged period of time, they all started selling their positions which led to the crash. On the other hand, since most traders viewed the Internet as some advanced technology that can benefit people in the long term, they gave it a very high value. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":369,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/06/ece6bcd8c4067ac8ae115cfc23fe31d6/39ebeaeadfca0c9c7fb986b01a91a602/lateximg_large.png","width":998},"regular":{"height":185,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/06/ece6bcd8c4067ac8ae115cfc23fe31d6/39ebeaeadfca0c9c7fb986b01a91a602/lateximg.png","width":500}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"290598a4-c53e-47d4-92f0-df2051a5277f","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":1}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.j